\f2\i0 \cf2 New Testament Refractal Tongues Insight\
\
The New Testament is a prism of divine revelation, refracting the light of God\'92s truth into multiple dimensions of understanding. Each Gospel, Epistle, and Apocalypse presents a facet of Christ\'92s full glory, preserving a unified message while revealing unique perspectives.\
\
The prism metaphor emphasizes semantic refracting, where words and themes, particularly light and tongues, split and multiply their meanings across contexts\'97expanding from a single source of divine truth to a spectrum of revelation.\
\
I. The Core Metaphor: The Prism as Scripture\'92s Multi-Layered Revelation\
	\'95	Light: Represents divine truth, purity, and revelation (John 1:4-5).\
	\'95	Prism: The textual diversity of Scripture refracting truth through multiple voices and cultural lenses.\
	\'95	Tongues: Language as a spectrum\'97from the tongues of Pentecost to the Word Made Flesh.\
\
Key Scriptures:\
	\'95	\'93In Him was life, and that life was the light of men.\'94 (John 1:4)\
	\'95	\'93We speak wisdom\'85 among the mature, but not the wisdom of this age.\'94 (1 Cor. 2:6-7)\
\
