	\'95	Pentecost: Languages reveal unity in diversity (Acts 2:3-4).\
	\'95	Tower of Babel Reversed: The tongues refract but return to one source\'97Christ.\
\
III. The New Testament as a Refracted Light Spectrum\
\
The four Gospels function as prismatic expressions of Christ\'92s singular truth, with unique angles yet a common light source:\
\
Matthew (The Light of Fulfillment)\
	\'95	Focus: Christ as the Jewish Messiah.\
	\'95	Key Refracted Themes: Kingdom, Covenant, Prophecy.\
\
Mark (The Light of Action)\
	\'95	Focus: Christ as the Suffering Servant.\
	\'95	Key Refracted Themes: Power, Suffering, Urgency.\
\
Luke (The Light of Compassion)\
	\'95	Focus: Christ as the Savior for all nations.\
	\'95	Key Refracted Themes: Mercy, Healing, Universality.\
\
John (The Light of Revelation)\
	\'95	Focus: Christ as the Divine Logos.\
	\'95	Key Refracted Themes: Identity, Divinity, New Creation.\
\
IV. The Epistles as Further Refracting Lenses\
\
The Pauline Epistles further refract the light by addressing specific theological issues:\
	\'95	Romans: The spectrum of Law and Grace.\
	\'95	Ephesians: The heavenly reality of the Church.\
	\'95	Philippians: The light of joy amid suffering.\
\
The General Epistles add even more nuance:\
	\'95	James: The visible fruit of faith.\
	\'95	Peter: Suffering and hope.\
	\'95	John: Love as the apex of divine truth.\
\
V. The Prism of Revelation: Full Eschatological Light\
\
Revelation does not introduce new light but gathers the entire spectrum back into one source:\
	\'95	The Throne of God as the Center of All Light (Rev. 22:5).\
	\'95	The Multilingual Worship of All Nations (Rev. 7:9).\
	\'95	The Blinding Glory of the Lamb (Rev. 21:23).\
\
VI. Theological Implications of the Prism Model\
\
1. Multiplicity without Contradiction:\
	\'95	The prism illustrates how many voices (the Gospels, Epistles) can communicate a unified reality without contradiction.\
\
2. Clarity through Refracting Words:\
	\'95	Words like faith, grace, covenant, and spirit are refracted into different contexts, but all reveal one truth.\
\
3. The Need for Illumination (Holy Spirit as Interpreter)\
	\'95	The Spirit interprets the refracted light, bringing clarity to divine truth (John 16:13).\
\
VII. Practical Applications: Reading the Bible Through the Prism Lens\
\
1. Approach Each Gospel as a Facet of the Whole:\
	\'95	Let the unique voices illuminate different aspects of Christ\'92s nature.\
\
2. Use the OT as the Prism\'92s Source:\
	\'95	Christ refracts prophetic light from Genesis to Malachi (Luke 24:27).\
\
3. Embrace the Tension of Diverse Writings:\
	\'95	Paul and James complement, not contradict.\
	\'95	Unity without uniformity.\
\
VIII. Conclusion: The Light Made Clear\
\
The prism of Scripture reveals a unified divine reality through refracted tongues of human language. Each biblical book presents the same light from a different angle, yet all converge in Christ, the True Light (John 1:9).\
\
Let the refracted tongues inspire deeper biblical literacy, cultural humility, and worship of the Word who makes all things known.\
